description.en: Indicates membership in an organization. Note that componency (e.g., departments of a corporation) are expressed using the more generic Organization.isPartOf property.

The human, group, or machine that consumes or acts upon an object or data. This higher-level grouping allows properties that are shared among its subclasses (Person, Organization, ....) to be anchored in one joint place, on the Agent class.

A GeoJSON Polygon coordinate listing representing the geometrical representation of the asset. Coordinates may be expressed in two or three dimensions. Ex: [[30.0, 10.0, 0.0], [40.0, 40.0, 2.0], [20.0, 40.0, 2.0], [10.0, 20.0, 2.0], [30.0, 10.0, 0.0]].
An asset may be mounted on some part of the building construction (e.g., a blind on a facade, a camera on a wall, etc).
Something which is placed inside of a building, but is not an integral part of that building's structure; e.g., furniture, equipment, systems, etc.
Indicates the architected space (site, building, level, room...) in which this building element is placed.
A part that constitutes a piece of a building's structural makeup. E.g., Facade, Wall, Slab, Roof, etc.

An administrative grouping of entities that are adressed and treated as a unit for some purpose. These entities may have some spatial arrangement (e.g., an apartment is typically contiguous) but that is not a requirement (see, e.g., a distributed campus consisting of spatially disjoint plots or buildings). Inclusion in a Collection is determined by the 'includes' field on a specific subclass.
Event ending timestamp.
Event start timestamp.

A temporally indexed entity, e.g., an observation, a lease, a construction project, etc. Can be instantaneous (timestamp property assigned) or have temporal extent (start and end properties assigned). Subclasses may define specific behaviour and requirements, e.g., on spatial indexing, agent participation, etc.
A fixed point for, e.g., a building structure. Commonly refered to as "insertion point" in CAD-programs. Used as origo for locally defined geometries.

A GeoJSON Polygon coordinate listing representing the geometrical representation of the space. Coordinates may be expressed in two or three dimensions. Ex: [[30.0, 10.0, 0.0], [40.0, 40.0, 2.0], [20.0, 40.0, 2.0], [10.0, 20.0, 2.0], [30.0, 10.0, 0.0]].
A contiguous part of the physical world that contains or can contain sub-spaces. E.g., a Region can contain many Sites, which in turn can contain many Buildings.
Brick tags associated with this interface.
URL link to an image that represents the person.
A natural person (i.e., an individual human being).

A campus represents a collection of location entities. The constituent locations may have differing legal ownership and utilization purposes, but they are generally perceived as a coherent unit or sub-region within a city or other region. E.g., a university campus, a hospital campus, a corporate campus, etc.

A portfolio is a grouping of buildings, sites, apartments, campuses, etc. that share some business-relevant commonality, e.g., are managed by the same company, are rented out to the same tenant, share utilization or legal definition (industrial vs commercial), etc.

A premises is an administrative grouping of spaces that are used for some commercial or industrial purpose by a real estate holder or tenant. E.g, a suite of offices, a shop, or an industrial workshop.
The legal/administrative representation of some lands and/or buildings. I.e., "Fastighet" (Swedish), "Ejendom" (Denmark), etc.
The object (e.g., property, equipment, etc) that this a lease of.
The agent leasing some leasable object, i.e., the user of the asset.
The agent leasing out some leasable object, i.e., the owner of the asset.
Indicates the contract regulating the terms of the lease in question.

Describes business-relevant area measurements typically associated with architected spaces. As the exact requirements on these measurements will vary from case to case or jurisdiction to jurisdiction, subclassing and specializing this definition is encouraged.
E.g., per Building Code

Describes business-relevant capacity measurements typically associated with architected spaces. As the exact requirements on these measurements will vary from case to case or jurisdiction to jurisdiction, subclassing and specializing this definition is encouraged.
Altitude
The angle between local coordinate system and a north-south meridian.
Latitude
Longitude
Encapsulates a georeference globally placing a spatially located entity in terms of latitude, longitude, altitude, and bearing.
The country, e.g., USA, Sweden, Argentina, or optionally a two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code, e.g., "SE", "US", etc.
An administrative geospatial unit larger than the individual real estate. For instance, "Lombary", "North America", "The Back Bay", "Elnätsområde Syd", etc.
URL link to an image/logo that represents the organization.
Indicates membership in an organization. Note that componency (e.g., departments of a corporation) are expressed using the more generic hasPart property.
Indicates parthood relations in organizations (e.g., departments of a corporation). Note that membership in an organization is expressed using the more specific hasMember property.
Indicates parthood relations in organizations (e.g., departments of a corporation). Note that membership in an organization is expressed using the Agent.isMemberOf property.
An organization of any sort (e.g., a business, association, project, consortium, tribe, etc.)
The payload message of this point event (e.g., a sensor reading, a command message, an exception message, etc.)

An event emanating from or targeting a Point; e.g., an individual Observation from a Sensor point, or an Actuation sent to a Command point. In other terms, the Points indicate the capability of some Space or Equipment to emit or accept data, while this class represents those actual data messages. Note that in most non-trivially sized systems, these events are not stored in the knowledge graph itself, but are rather forwarded to some C&C system or time series database.
Physical address of the architecture (site, building, sub-building, entrance room, etc.) in question.
Links an Architecture to BuildingElement that is contained in the Space.
A designed/landscaped (or potentially designed/landscaped) part of the physical world that has a 3D spatial extent. E.g., a building site, a building, levels within the building, rooms, etc.
